  "body": "Your guide to the WSJ’s exclusive reporting and analysis.               Is this email difficult to read? View in browser   https://10point.cmail19.com/t/d-e-gkulkyk-dknirndy-z/                                                                                                   \r\n\r\nSponsored By\r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n✏️ A shooter was detained at the White House Correspondents’ Dinner, where President Trump was bundled from the stage. I was there with colleagues, as all hell broke loose in the ballroom of the Washington Hilton. The event brought together many of America’s top government officials in a single room, alongside business executives, celebrities and journalists.  What we know so far [https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/white-house-correspondents-dinner-trump-shooting].\r\n\r\nEmma Tucker\r\n\r\nEditor in Chief, The Wall Street Journal\r\n\r\nTODAY'S HEADLINES\r\n\r\n1\r\n\r\nThe  31-year-old suspect [https://www.wsj.com/us-news/caltech-grad-teacher-of-the-month-named-as-washington-shooting-suspect-310cf6fb] in the shooting is a Caltech grad who recently won a “teacher of the month” award. The event left some in the room, from cabinet secretaries to aides and reporters, grappling with the  new reality [https://www.wsj.com/us-news/a-shooter-throws-trumps-night-with-the-press-into-chaos-9db9b9f7] that such violence has become a regular occurrence.  Here’s the latest [https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/white-house-correspondents-dinner-trump-shooting].  Trump scrapped a trip by U.S. envoys Steve Witkoff and Jared Kushner to Pakistan for talks with Iran,  leaving himself tough choices [https://www.wsj.com/world/middle-east/aborted-pakistan-trip-leaves-trump-with-tough-choices-on-iran-talks-e062f8fd] over how to push for concessions to strike a deal.  Follow our live coverage [https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/iran-war-us-trump-2026].  Gannon Ken Van Dyke—who allegedly made more than $400,000 in part by  using classified information to bet [https://www.wsj.com/us-news/the-soldier-accused-of-maduro-bets-army-people-dont-get-the-business-stuff-5d9e90ff] on the ousting of Nicolás Maduro—was a U.S. Army soldier simultaneously chasing business success. He didn’t respond to requests for comment.  America’s pandemic car bubble is  trapping buyers in debt [https://www.wsj.com/business/autos/car-owners-debt-negative-equity-3cfcd031], with the average amount a borrower with negative equity carries on a vehicle up more than 40% since 2021.\r\n\r\nFROM THE MARKETS\r\n\r\n2\r\n\r\nThe  AI frenzy is back [https://www.wsj.com/finance/stocks/the-ai-frenzy-is-back-and-lifting-the-entire-stock-market-to-record-highs-5d5586ac] and lifting the entire stock market to record highs, though signs of froth are everywhere, writes James Mackintosh.  Moves in the loan market show that Wall Street is sorting software companies into  winners and losers [https://www.wsj.com/finance/investing/wall-street-is-sorting-software-companies-into-winners-and-losers-e44fe73b] amid fears of AI disruption in the sector.\r\n\r\nREAD IT HERE FIRST\r\n\r\n3\r\n\r\nBill Perkins told WSJ why he doesn’t think you should wait to spend your money.                                            \r\n\r\nThe founder of Skylar Capital Management wagers in the notoriously boom-or-bust energy markets, while also working on two startups. But there’s nothing he seems quite as dedicated to as  enjoying his life—and fortune [https://www.wsj.com/business/die-with-zero-bill-perkins-wsj-money-interview-2a4440f4]. The Journal’s Gunjan Banerji sat down with the hedge-fund manager before one of the biggest energy shocks in years, and he explained why he’s hell-bent on “dying with zero.”\r\n\r\nStay tuned for the next episode [https://www.wsj.com/personal-finance/the-wsj-money-interview-2dd1e861?mod=article_inline&_gl=1*185r7zm*_ga*MTcyNTA2MTY3MC4xNzExNTU0NTI0] of The WSJ Money Interview.            \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n4\r\n\r\nThis small St. Louis suburb is leading America’s crusade against data centers.\r\n\r\nIn Festus, Mo., a  backlash against the construction of data centers [https://www.wsj.com/us-news/the-small-midwest-community-leading-americas-crusade-against-data-centers-92621c55] has reached a fever pitch, reports Will Parker. When the City Council last month approved a proposal by a St. Louis developer to build a data center to accommodate AI, residents erupted in protest. In the spring elections, a landslide vote removed four City Council incumbents who backed the project. With the midterms approaching, opposition to AI as well as the construction of data centers to support it is evolving into a campaign issue for all politicians. More than 90 local governments have enacted or are considering measures to limit data-center construction.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nGo inside the U.S.-China relationship.\r\n\r\nSign up for the WSJ China newsletter [https://www.wsj.com/newsletters/wsj-china] to get exclusive insights on the contest between the U.S. and China, brought to you every week by the WSJ’s top China correspondent.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n              CONTENT FROM: FOX ONE          MLB on FOX and More on FOX One   [http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/clk?id=7145480861&iu=/2]\r\n\r\nThe 2026 MLB season is in full swing and streaming live all season long on FOX One. Catch over 85 regular season games—including 23 Saturday matchups—plus the All-Star Game and the World Series on the FOX One app, the streaming home for everything FOX. Stream FOX Sports, FOX News, FOX Business and FOX Weather alongside hit entertainment shows live or on-demand, all in one place.\r\n\r\nLearn More [http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/clk?id=7145480861&iu=/2]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nEXPERT TAKE\r\n\r\n5\r\n\r\nQ: What makes a truly great entrepreneur?\r\n\r\nFor three decades, Jonathan Bean and Blaine McCormick have asked business historians and thought leaders to rank the nation’s greatest entrepreneurs and businesspeople. As a part of WSJ’s yearlong series, “ USA250 [https://www.wsj.com/usa250?]: The Story of the World’s Greatest Economy,” the two researchers wrote about  what their rankings say about both business and leadership [https://www.wsj.com/business/entrepreneurship/best-entrepreneurs-us-history-23c83c23].\r\n\r\nA: While business visionaries are often the true agents of change, ranking them raises an inevitable question: What exactly does greatness in business mean? So, for our last survey in 2021, we asked our experts to rank “factors of greatness” that might explain the names in their rankings. (Note that since the list is five years old, some businesspeople at the forefront of innovation right now aren’t represented, like those in AI-related businesses.)\r\n\r\nAt the top of the experts’ list: “ability to imagine or envision the future” and “impact of product or service in reordering American life.” Contrast that with a factor they ranked much lower: “created wealth for shareholders.”\r\n\r\nIn other words, the entrepreneurs who loom largest in American history—Henry Ford, John D. Rockefeller, Steve Jobs, Andrew Carnegie, the top four names on our list—aren’t remembered for optimizing stock prices. They are appreciated for the way they changed how people lived, worked, consumed and thought about tomorrow. (Rounding out our list are luminaries from a range of eras and industries: Bill Gates, Thomas Edison, Sam Walton, Jeff Bezos, Walt Disney and J.P. Morgan.)\r\n\r\nSEE THE STORY\r\n\r\n6\r\n\r\nWatch how the energy crisis is spreading across the world.            \r\n\r\nDANIEL KISS\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn a war between oil exporters, petroleum importers are finding themselves at the front lines of a global energy crisis. Now, governments across the world are taking drastic steps to combat the crisis that range from cash handouts to fuel rationing. Here’s  what the measures look like in practice [https://www.wsj.com/finance/commodities-futures/see-how-the-energy-crisis-is-spreading-across-the-world-dc497d72].\r\n\r\nHAPPENING THIS WEEK\r\n\r\n7\r\n\r\nElon Musk’s lawsuit against Sam Altman and OpenAI is set to begin in Oakland, Calif.  Tuesday: The Conference Board’s consumer confidence survey for April.  Wednesday: The Federal Reserve announces a rate decision, where it is expected to leave the federal-funds target range unchanged at 3.50%-3.75%.  Thursday: The advance estimate of first-quarter U.S. gross domestic product, which will give investors an indication of how America’s economy has fared during the war in the Middle East. The Labor Department reports weekly jobless claims.\r\n\r\nTHE NUMBER\r\n\r\n8\r\n\r\n          >40%          \r\n\r\nThe share of  America’s aviation mechanics [https://www.wsj.com/business/airlines/aircraft-technicians-make-six-figures-and-airlines-cant-find-enough-of-them-efdb798c] who are over 60 and approaching retirement, according to a report from Oliver Wyman management consultants and the Aviation Technician Education Council. Though many aircraft technicians make six figures, airlines can’t find enough of them.\r\n\r\nAND FINALLY...\r\n\r\n9\r\n\r\nSan Francisco is going nuts over a giant sea lion named Chonkers.\r\n\r\nThe 2,000-pound Steller sea lion is about  three times the size [https://www.wsj.com/lifestyle/san-francisco-sea-lion-pier-39-chonkers-145628c0] of the California sea lions that typically inhabit the San Francisco Bay. He swam up to a dock on Pier 39 a month ago and decided to stay—and online commenters can’t seem to get enough. “Chonkers the stellar sea lion is back at Pier 39 today!” reads one post. Another is entitled, “Pier 39’s Steller Sea Lion Belly Scratch Action!”\r\n\r\nBEYOND THE NEWSROOM\r\n\r\n10\r\n\r\nWSJ | Buy Side: See the  top pet insurance companies [https://www.wsj.com/buyside/personal-finance/pet-insurance/best-pet-insurance] to safeguard your wallet from high pet medical bills.               \r\n\r\nAbout Us\r\n\r\nThe 10-Point is your guide to The Wall Street Journal's reporting and analysis you can't get anywhere else. Your subscription makes our journalism possible.\r\n\r\nToday's newsletter was curated and edited by Conor Grant and Bryony Watson in collaboration with Editor in Chief Emma Tucker. Got a tip for us? Here's  how to submit [https://www.wsj.com/tips].\r\n\r\n Unsubscribe [http://www.wsj.com/newsletters?unsub=197&addr=d4ae6d32bd4db70c10900a8884d402000bb7d1fd78e887a1ed41df81457d62ff3e]      Unsubscribe https://10point.cmail19.com/t/d-u-gkulkyk-dknirndy-v/            Newsletters & Alerts [https://www.wsj.com/newsletters]            Contact Us [https://customercenter.wsj.com/public?url=https://customercenter.wsj.com/view/contactus.html]            Privacy Notice [https://dowjones.com/privacy-notice]            Cookie Notice [https://dowjones.com/cookie-notice]                             Dow Jones & Company, Inc. 4300 U.S. Ro‌ute 1 No‌rth Monm‌outh Junc‌tion, N‌J 088‌52\r\n\r\nYou are currently subscribed as wschenk@gmail.com. For further assistance, please contact Customer Service at support@wsj.com or 1-800-JOURNAL.\r\n\r\nCopyright 2026 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.   |   All Rights Reserved.\r\n",
